What is R?

R is a programming language for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing.

It is free!

Answers to questions in:

https://stackoverflow.com/

https://www.r-bloggers.com/

Packages

  • The capabilities of R are extended through user-created packages

  • Packages allow specialised statistical techniques, graphical devices, import/export capabilities, reporting tools (Rmarkdown, knitr, Sweave), etc.

Tidyverse

Group of packages considered a “dialect of the R language”.

Increasingly popular in the R ecosystem.

The packages of tidyverse provide a cohesive collection of functions to deal with common data science tasks, including data import, cleaning, transformation and visualisation.

To practice

Basic syntax

  • Comment symbol is #
  • Variables are created using <-
  • Important: Lower and uppr cases do count!
random <- 30

print(random/10)
## [1] 3

Upload a dataset

If data is in xlsx format

library(xlsx)
data <- read.xlsx("databasename.xls", sheetName = "Content")

If data is in Text format

library(readr)
dataset <- read_csv(NULL)

If data is in Stata format

library(haven)
dataset <- read_stata(NULL)

Pipping

Pipping refers to chaining actions in a series of steps. The key element to pipping is %>%

my_data %>%
  do_this_thing() %>%
  now_do_that_thing() %>%
  and_one_more()

Separating and uniting columns

Separating and uniting two columns

#To separate
data %>% separate(Variable, into = c("X", "Y"), sep = "")

#To unite
data %>% unite(Variable, c("X", "Y"), sep = "_", remove = TRUE, na.rm = FALSE)

In our example

movies <- movies %>% separate(Title, into = c("Title", "Year"), sep = "[()]") #A bracket expression is a list of characters enclosed by ‘[’ and ‘]’. It matches any single character in that list. If the first character of the list is the caret ‘^’, then it matches any character not in the list
# Uniting two columns
# movies <- movies %>% unite(Title, c("Title", "Year"), sep = "_", remove = TRUE, na.rm = FALSE)
# 
# movies <- movies %>% separate(Title, into = c("Title", "Year"), sep = "_") #A bracket expression is a list of characters enclosed by '[' and ']'. It matches any single character in that list. If the first character of the list is the caret '^', then it matches any character not in the list

Mutate

Create new variables within the original dataset

my_data <- my_data %>%
mutate(variable = expression)

In our example:

Let’s get the log of variable rating

movies %>%
  mutate(log_rating = log(Rating))

To replace strings in the data

# Replacing a single string

movies[11,2] <- "Birdman"
movies[11,3] <- "2014"


# Replacing multiple strings under the same condition

# movies2 <- movies %>% mutate(Title = replace(Title, Title == "Birdman or ", "Birdman")) %>%
#                        mutate(Year = replace(Year, Year == "The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance", "2014"))

To convert variable types

movies <- movies %>% 
  mutate(TotalVotes = parse_number(TotalVotes)) %>%
  mutate(Budget  = parse_number(Budget))  
## Warning: 1 parsing failure.
## row col expected                                                                                                  actual
##  67  -- a number Production Co:        Pathé,        BBC Films,        Proud Films              See more<U+00A0><U+00BB>
# To create dummy variables
movies <- movies %>% mutate(drama = ifelse(Genre1 == "Drama", 1, 0)) %>% 
                     mutate(dramaorbio = ifelse(Genre1 == "Drama"|Genre1 == "Biography", 1, 0)) %>%
                     mutate(log_rating = log(Rating))

Omit missing values

movies <- movies %>%
  na.omit()

Arrange

# for ascending order:

movies_arranged <- movies %>% arrange(Rating)

# for descending order:
movies_arranged <- movies %>% arrange(-Rating)
# movies <- movies %>% arrange(desc(Rating))

# to sort by one variable then another
movies_arranged <- movies %>% arrange(Year,desc(Rating))

Filter

Action <- movies %>% 
  filter(Genre1 == "Action")

Select

# keeps all rows, but only retain the columns for VARIABLE1 and VARIABLE2
# data %>% select(VARIABLE 1, VARIABLE2)

submovies <- movies %>% 
  select(Title, Year, Rating, TotalVotes)

Reminder: arrange, filter, select DON’T change the original data set. Instead they return a new one, which you can assign to a variable

Adventure <- movies %>%
  filter(Genre1 == "Adventure") %>% 
  select(Title, Year, Rating, TotalVotes) %>% 
  arrange(Year,desc(Rating), desc(TotalVotes))

Group et summarise

# Group by gender and obtain the mean and median of their rating
summovies <- movies %>%
  group_by(Genre1) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_rating = mean(Rating),
    median_rating = median(Rating, na.rm = TRUE), #Handling with missing values
    std_dev = sd(Rating),
    count = n(),
    mean_ratingF = mean(VotesF),
    mean_ratingM = mean(VotesM)
  )

print(summovies)

##Plot using ggplot2

# Barplot

summovies %>% ggplot(aes(x = Genre1, y = mean_rating)) +
                       geom_col()

summovies %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Genre1, y = mean_rating)) + 
  geom_col(fill="skyblue", alpha=0.5)

# Grouped bar plot

summovies_long %>% 
 ggplot() +
  # add bar for each discipline colored by gender
  geom_bar(aes(x = Genre1, y = ratingFH, fill = Gender),
           stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  # name axes and remove gap between bars and y-axis
  scale_y_continuous("Rating", expand = c(0, 0)) +
  scale_x_discrete("Movie Genre") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#468189", "#9DBEBB")) +
  # remove grey theme
  theme_classic(base_size = 18) +
  # rotate x-axis and remove superfluous axis elements
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
                                   hjust = 1, vjust = 0),
        axis.line = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank())
